-> SQL commands are categorized into five types:

DDL (Data Definition Language) â†’ CREATE, ALTER, DROP, TRUNCATE
DML (Data Manipulation Language) â†’ INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE
DQL (Data Query Language) â†’ SELECT
TCL (Transaction Control Language) â†’ COMMIT, ROLLBACK, SAVEPOINT
DCL (Data Control Language) â†’ GRANT, REVOKE


-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
| Command   | Removes Data?          | Can be Rolled Back?   | Affects Structure?  |
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
| DELETE    | Yes (selected rows)    | Yes (COMMIT/ROLLBACK) | âŒ No               |
| TRUNCATE  | Yes (all rows)         | âŒ No                 | âŒ No               |
| DROP      | Yes (entire table)     | âŒ No                 | âœ… Yes (removes structure) |
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------


-------------------------------------------------------------------
| Constraint   | Uniqueness  | NULL Allowed?        | Usage            |
-------------------------------------------------------------------
| PRIMARY KEY  | âœ… Unique   | âŒ No                | One per table    |
| UNIQUE KEY   | âœ… Unique   | âœ… Yes (one NULL)    | Multiple per table |
-------------------------------------------------------------------

## JOIN
-> INNER JOIN
-> LEFT JOIN
-> RIGHT JOIN
-> FULL OUTER JOIN
Ex:
ðŸŸ¢ SELECT C.OrderID, C.CustomerName, O.OrderDate
FROM Orders O INNER JOIN Customers C ON O.CustomerID=C.CustomerID;
